Broadway, east side, between Vietor and Elmhurst Avenues, showing in a set of 4 views the Woodward-Vietor house. The owners of this property were Theo Vietor, 1852, T. Vietor, 1860, and H. Vietor in 1873.

Nathaniel Woodward, married Mary, daughter of Captain Samuel Moore in the early 18th century. The original, homestead stood some distance to the north and was torn down about 1880. This area has been part of the Woodward farm since 1666. One of the out-buildings a barn was occupied by the British as a hospital during the Revolutionary War.

Broadway, west side, opposite Vietor Avenue, showing four views of the Samuel Moore house. It is said that the center structure was erected in 1663 and the remainder by Samuel or Benjamin Moore in 1760 or 1770. It was removed to make way for the Independent Subway line about 1930. Other owners were J.J. Moore, 1852-1873; John Perry, 1867; and O.H. Perry, in 1891. It is stated that Clement Clarke Moore, the author of 'Twas the Night Before Christmas', was also an owner. See other views for more data.

Broadway, west side, opposite Vietor Avenue. In view one the street in the foreground is Laurel Hill Boulevard. At the right background is Broadway, the site of the house and surrounding land was owned by the Rev. John Moore who died in 1657. His son Samuel purchased the tract in 1662. His son Benjamin was followed by Lieutenant Samuel who was a son of Benjamin. He died in 1788. A part of this house was built by him. John a brother of Lieut. Samuel was the next owner. He died in 1827. The center structure dates probably back to 1666 and was the original house of Samuel Moore son of the Rev. John Moore. The house was enlarged in 1760 probably by Lieut. Samuel Moore. It is also questionably stated to be the headquarters of General Howe during the Revolution. Note the old time saving devise for drawing water.
